metadata.title: Boeing-Stearman Model 75
aws::graph::propositions: Stearman 70 was powered by a 215 hp (160 kW) Lycoming radial engine.
Stearman 70 was designated XPT-943 for evaluation.
Model 73 was the initial production version of the Boeing-Stearman aircraft.
61 Model 73 aircraft were built for U.S. Navy as NS.
Model 73 was also built in export variants.
Model 73L3 was a version for the Philippines.
Model 73L3 was powered by 200 hp (150 kW) R-680-4 or R-680C1 engines.
Model A73B1 consisted of seven aircraft for Cuban Air Force.
Model A73B1 was powered by 235 hp (175 kW) Wright R-790 Whirlwind engines.
Model A73B1 aircraft were delivered between 1939 and 1940.
Model A73L3 was an improved version for the Philippines.
Three Model A73L3 aircraft were built.
Stearman 75 was evaluated by the U.S. Army as a primary trainer.
Stearman 75 was also known as X75.
The X75L3 became the PT-13 prototype.
Variants of the Stearman 75 formed the PT-17 family.

text:
### Company designations
Stearman 70
Company designation for prototype, powered by 215 hp (160 kW) Lycoming radial engine, designated XPT-943 for evaluation
Model 73
Initial production version, 61 built for U.S. Navy as NS plus export variants
Model 73L3
Version for the Philippines, powered by 200 hp (150 kW) R-680-4 or R-680C1 engines, seven built
Model A73B1
Seven aircraft for Cuban Air Force powered by 235 hp (175 kW) Wright R-790 Whirlwind, delivered 19391940
Model A73L3
Improved version for the Philippines, three built
Stearman 75
(or X75) Evaluated by the U.S. Army as a primary trainer, the X75L3 became the PT-13 prototype. Variants of the 75 formed the PT-17 family.
